rename.from: Look into/fix sphinx build warnings (sound like typos)

body: some of this may have been fixed by #408
Hey Pedigo, I'm a little confused with this issue.  Where are the 'build warnings' supposed to show up?  I didn't encounter them when I installed graspy from github.

@pauladkisson 
- Look at a [recent PR](https://github.com/neurodata/graspy/pull/421)
- Scroll down to bottom where it says "All checks have passed" and there are a bunch of lines that say "details" at the end. These are automated checks that run every time someone makes a PR. 
- Click on "details" next to where it says "mixed content - graspy" 
- Should bring you to something like [this](https://app.netlify.com/sites/graspy/deploys/5f525bb2dd0fc000072c437c) these are the logs from the build of our documentation
- If you scroll through you should see something like: 
```
8:27:56 AM: /opt/build/repo/graspy/cluster/gclust.py:docstring of graspy.cluster.GaussianCluster:38: WARNING: Bullet list ends without a blank line; unexpected unindent.
8:27:56 AM: /opt/build/repo/graspy/cluster/gclust.py:docstring of graspy.cluster.GaussianCluster:64: WARNING: Unexpected indentation.
/opt/build/repo/graspy/inference/latent_position_test.py:docstring of graspy.inference.LatentPositionTest:40: WARNING: Explicit markup ends without a blank line; unexpected unindent.
8:27:56 AM: /opt/build/repo/graspy/inference/latent_position_test.py:docstring of graspy.inference.LatentPositionTest:43: WARNING: Explicit markup ends without a blank line; unexpected unindent.
8:27:56 AM: /opt/build/repo/graspy/inference/latent_position_test.py:docstring of graspy.inference.LatentPositionTest.fit_predict:6: WARNING: Unexpected indentation.
8:27:56 AM: /opt/build/repo/graspy/inference/latent_position_test.py:docstring of graspy.inference.LatentPositionTest.fit_predict:11: WARNING: Title underline too short.
8:27:56 AM: Returns
8:27:56 AM: ------
8:27:56 AM: /opt/build/repo/graspy/inference/latent_position_test.py:docstring of graspy.inference.LatentPositionTest.fit_predict:11: WARNING: Unexpected section title.
8:27:56 AM: Returns
8:27:56 AM: ------
8:27:56 AM: /opt/build/repo/graspy/inference/latent_position_test.py:docstring of graspy.inference.LatentPositionTest:72: WARNING: Unknown target name: "p_value_1".
8:27:56 AM: /opt/build/repo/graspy/inference/latent_position_test.py:docstring of graspy.inference.LatentPositionTest:72: WARNING: Unknown target name: "p_value_2".
8:27:56 AM: /opt/build/repo/graspy/inference/latent_position_test.py:docstring of graspy.inference.LatentPositionTest.fit_predict:26: WARNING: Unknown target name: "p_value".
```
The goal is to fix the documentation generation to not have these warnings. I'd just focus on the ones for `LatentPositionTest` to start (or even just the ones about "unknown target name"), because that will let you just focus on one class in the code for now. You will have to learn a bit about how the documentation gets generated. There is something called a docstring in python (the one you will start with is [here](https://github.com/neurodata/graspy/blob/ca4001315b2d00d19437609afa6bdf96577fd7ce/graspy/inference/latent_position_test.py#L25)) which is in the code, but a tool called sphinx converts into out documentation pages. The warnings above are basically saying that when sphinx is run, there are some issues with how the docstrings get converted to documentation.

Ok, this is definitely helpful.  I can see the warnings in the deploy details that you mentioned, and it should be easy enough to fix a few docstrings, but I've never worked on a project to this scale before.  How can I check my work to make sure that the issues are resolved?

@pauladkisson I think the easiest thing for you in this case will be to make a draft PR sooner rather than later. This will cause netlify (the thing that builds our docs) to trigger a build online, which will generate all of those logs, and will let you check your work to see if the errors stop.

Other option is to build the documentation locally on your machine. Instructions for that are [here](https://github.com/neurodata/graspy/tree/master/docs)

Thanks, yeah, I just found the instructions for installing sphinx and building the docs.  I was able to get it to run and display the appropriate warnings, but I also got a weird error that didn't show up in the netlify version:

```
Notebook error:
CellExecutionError in tutorials/inference/latent_distribution_test.ipynb:
------------------
ldt_dcorr = LatentDistributionTest("dcorr", metric="euclidean", n_bootstraps=100)
ldt_dcorr.fit(A1, A2)
------------------

```

Do you know what's going on?

So using the ignore error setting listed above, I am able to work on the documentation fixes.  When I get through them, I will remove the ignore error setting, submit a PR, and see if the error persists.

1. @pauladkisson feel free to @ me whenever anything concerning latent distribution test causes issues cuz much of it is my code, so i likely will know. 
2. wrap multiline code in ``` please
3. despite 1, i have no idea what's going on, since it passes for me.

actually, i have a conjecture: i think i changed an argument that used to be called distance to "metric" in #366 . so maybe it uses an outdated version of graspy. why / how to check? me not knows. Ben?

Hey @alyakin314! Yeah, I'm not sure what's going on with that since I just cloned the repo yesterday...

For the other warnings, most of it is fairly simple to fix (funky indents, skipped lines, etc.) but I did some digging on the internet, and it looks like sphinx itself has a bug where it doesn't recognize variables with a trailing underscore (p_value_1_, p_value_2_, etc.).  So, I could change the actual variable names to omit the underscore, but I don't know if I would need to change them elsewhere.  @bdpedigo lmk what you think.

@pauladkisson you should be careful with changing those. some of them are used in tutorial notebooks, so they may break if u change the names. furthremore, i think some of those variables, such as p_value and null_distribution follow the same convention between ldt and lpt, and are even mentioned in BaseInference's docs. so you should search through repo and change the names everywhere where apropriate, if you intend on changing 'em.
